Upon successful completion of this course, students are expected to:
• be able to discuss regional differences in the PRC, in particular issues facing the western regions of China;
• understand the relevance of this regional approach to the main trends in China’s contemporary global interactions;
• demonstrate an improved ability to present clear oral and written analysis of issues of political economy.

Upon successful completion of this course, students are expected:
• to have a critical understanding of issues of regional governance in East Asia;
• to understand how various regional institutions operate;
• to be able to use relevant theoretical concepts to aid understanding of regional governance in East Asia.
• to demonstrate an improved ability to present clear oral and written analysis of issues of political economy.

After completing this course, students should:
1) have a basic grasp of modern Chinese history and some of its key events;
2) be able to critically analyze the different uses of the past in the present;
3) have an understanding of the ways film and literature represent memory and trauma.

After completing this course, students should:
1) have a firm grasp of basic genre theory;
2) be familiar with the different East Asian film industries and some of their directors;
3) be able to use genre as a critical tool in analyzing and making films;
4) have a basic understanding of film language and film production.

Upon successful completion of this course, students should be able to:
1. understand the critical issues in Hong Kong and Mainland China integration;
2. identify the underlying factors and mechanisms that drive the dynamic interaction between Hong Kong and Mainland China;
3. critically analyse significant social, political, economic and environmental issues in the process of Hong Kong and Mainland integration.

After taking the course, students will acquire
- An adequate understanding of Chinese political, economic and legal institutions;
- A good grasp of the major initiatives and policies behind the Era of the Reform and Open Door, which is still on-going;
- An ability to analyze specific reform policies given China’s unique national conditions as well as the country’s interactions with the global community.
- A capacity to assess the achievements or shortcomings of reform policies in relation to the country’s basic political and economic structure.
- An ability to make suggestions regarding how certain political or economic reform policies can be improved to suit the fast-shifting changes in the 21st century.

After completing the course, students should:
1) be equipped with the essential techniques to examine the artistic features of any art work;
2) have a basic understanding of Chinese art history and aesthetics since 1900;
3) be able to critically analyze various aesthetic and artistic issues in Chinese art, and to participate in relevant scholarly debates.

On completion of the course, students will be able to:
1) tell the functions and roles of museums in society and the world;
2) understand core museology principles and concepts;
3) apply the above theories to study any museum critically and professionally;
4) appreciate Chinese artworks and artifacts from a museological perspective, such as display method;
5) explain the local and global significance of Chinese art as expressed in museums;
6) integrate issues of cross-cultural interaction in their analysis of a variety of museum objects and images;
7) reflect upon the relevance of historical objects and images in China and the world.

On completion of the course, students:
1) should have a strong understanding of the main issues in China’s relationships in Asia;
2) be able to discuss these issues critically using major theoretical concepts in International Relations and related disciplines.

After completing the course, students should:
1) be equipped with the essential techniques to examine the pictorial features of any Chinese painting;
2) have a basic understanding of Chinese painting history;
3) be able to critically analyze various aesthetic and artistic issues in Chinese painting, and to participate in relevant scholarly debates.

On completion of this course, successful students will be able to
 define a topic in Chinese Studies and conduct research into that topic using appropriate skills and resources;
 for those with knowledge of the Chinese language: acquire Chinese language sources from libraries or internet databases;
 make constructive use of influential theoretical paradigms.

Upon completion of the course, successful students:

● will have developed skills and experience in research;
● will have gained experience of project management and teamwork;
● will have developed further their report writing skills.
